Sep 19 2006 	Some good Some bad	First the good: 1. Close (a five minute walk) to a metro station, and a 10 minute walk to the waterfront piers where the boat leave from. A $5.40 ride to the Notre Dame baslilica and about a $5 ride to the heart of the Vieux Montreal old town fine restaurants.2. A complimentary hot breakfast that was on par with much pricier hotels. Several choices too, and the waitres did not charge us more for ordering extra bacon - a generous touch.3. A fairly comfortabe - although a slightly worn - ambiece that may put some off, yet apeal to pothers due to its inherent quirkiness and charm. Now, I noticed a few posts which mentioned the rooms being too small - I did not find this was the case with our room. Well, our room was well-sized and while the facilities were certainly not what you would find in a Hilton, the room did have a certain charm about it.4. A polite, homely and helpful staff, including the proprietor.5. Well priced. I did not shop around too much, so I really cant say if this is much less expensive than the competition, but based on my limited search, it seemed to be near the bottom of the price list in the old Montreal area.Now the bad:1. There is no elevator. The stairs are steep and if you are coming back to your room after a hard day's sightseeing, you crtainy dont want to climb 3 setsof stairs, do you? Take a room on the ground or first floor, or dont bother with this hotel.2. There was no bright light in the room. Not good for someone who wants to read. Having said that, there were three lamps.3. I did not notice any parking on the premises.4. The dinner menu in the restaurant is quite limited and expensive for its class, the 'house beer' is just ok and quite expensive, and the bar closes at 11 pm.5. The neighbourhood seems to be a mix of upmarket housing and outright poverty / drug abuse. I noticed at least 40 or so homeless people in the vicinity of the hotel. I feel sorry for these people, and will be honest - at no time 